\end{table}

% ======================================================================
\section{Analysis}
\label{sec:analysis}

\subsection{The Fluent Hallucinator Finding}
\label{sec:f6}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{fig_f6_finding.png}
\caption{The fluent hallucinator effect. \textbf{Left}: V3 ranking with truthfulness gate (CAMEL-AI / SmolagentS / FlowSearcher form the top tier). \textbf{Right}: V1 ranking without the gate. GPT-Researcher jumps from rank~5 to rank~1 despite fabricating 97.5\% of its citations. Kendall~$\tau{=}0.50$.}
\label{fig:f6}
\end{figure}

To isolate the effect of the truthfulness gate, we recompute rankings using the V1 additive composite $0.4\,u + 0.4\,j + 0.2\,s$ that ignores reachability entirely. The result (Figure~\ref{fig:f6}) is dramatic:

\vspace{1mm}
\begin{center}
\footnotesize
\begin{tabular}{ll}
\textbf{V3 (with gate):} & CAMEL-AI $>$ SmolagentS $>$ FlowSearcher $\gg$ DeerFlow $>$ GPT-R $>$ LDR $>$ ODR $>$ STORM $>$ II-R \\
\textbf{V1 (no gate):}  & GPT-R $>$ CAMEL-AI $>$ SmolagentS $>$ FlowSearcher $>$ ODR $>$ II-R $>$ DeerFlow $>$ LDR $>$ STORM \\
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
\vspace{1mm}

The Kendall $\tau$ between these rankings is 0.50: a substantial reordering driven entirely by the gate. GPT-Researcher rises from rank~5 to rank~1, leapfrogging the entire top tier; it produces the most fluent, best-structured reports with the highest checklist pass rates and analysis-depth scores, yet 97.5\% of its cited URLs do not exist in the sandbox (Table~\ref{tab:fab}).

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Citation fabrication rate by agent (1 -- HTTP-200 reachability over all cited URLs). Three agents fabricate near-completely; one fabricates a quarter of citations; the rest cite real pages or cite very few URLs at all.}
\label{tab:fab}
\vspace{1mm}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lrr@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Agent} & \textbf{Cited URLs} & \textbf{Fabrication \%} \\
\midrule
Langchain-ODR    & 1{,}247 & \textbf{99.1\%} \\
II-Researcher    &   395 & \textbf{98.5\%} \\
GPT-Researcher   & 1{,}870 & \textbf{97.5\%} \\
DeerFlow         &   406 & 87.4\% \\
SmolagentS       & 1{,}397 & 23.9\% \\
FlowSearcher     & 1{,}577 & 24.0\% \\
LDR              &    67 & 10.4\% \\
CAMEL-AI         & 3{,}152 & \phantom{0}8.8\% \\
STORM            &     0 & --- (cites nothing) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\textbf{Why this matters.} An LLM judge~\citep{llmjudge2024} evaluating the same reports without URL verification would rank GPT-Researcher first by a wide margin. This is not a hypothetical failure mode. It mirrors the real-world problem of hallucinated citations in AI-assisted academic writing, where plausible-looking references pass peer review despite being entirely fabricated. Because our corpus is frozen and fully known, URL verification is deterministic, complete, and zero-cost.

\subsection{Scoring Ablation}
\label{sec:ablation}

We probe the V3 composite by zeroing each scoring dimension in turn, recomputing the Bradley-Terry leaderboard, and measuring rank stability via Kendall~$\tau$ (Table~\ref{tab:ablation}). The V1$\leftrightarrow$V3 inversion in \S\ref{sec:f6} is the headline rank-altering perturbation; here we study finer-grained leave-one-out effects.

\begin{table}[t]
\centering
\caption{Leave-one-out ablation on the V3 composite (9 agents, 30 common tasks). Reachability is again the only dimension whose removal substantially reorders the leaderboard (the bottom-six fabrication-fed cluster collapses upward). Quality dimensions are correlated and individually rank-irrelevant given the present spread of agents.}
\label{tab:ablation}
\vspace{1mm}
\small
\begin{tabular}{@{}lcl@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Dropped dimension} & \textbf{$\tau$ vs.\ V3} & \textbf{Effect on top tier} \\
\midrule
url\_coverage      & 1.00 & none \\
quote\_match       & 0.94 & top tier intact; bottom shuffles \\
checklist\_judge   & 1.00 & none \\
citation\_alignment & 0.94 & top tier intact; bottom shuffles \\
analysis\_depth    & 1.00 & none \\
presentation       & 1.00 & none \\
spec\_compliance   & 1.00 & none \\
\textbf{reachability} & \textbf{0.50} & \textbf{GPT-Researcher 5$\to$1; cf.\ \S\ref{sec:f6}} \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

Three observations emerge. \textbf{(1)} Reachability is the dominant rank-altering dimension; removing it yields the V1 ranking (Kendall~$\tau{=}0.50$), with GPT-Researcher leapfrogging the entire top tier. \textbf{(2)} Reachability, quote match, and citation alignment are tightly correlated (Spearman $\rho > 0.85$ pairwise): agents that cite real URLs also quote them accurately and align cited evidence with claims. Grounding behaves as an all-or-nothing capability rather than a gradient — fabricators fabricate everything, and grounders ground everything. \textbf{(3)} Quality-dimension weights are largely irrelevant under the present agent landscape: sweeping any single quality weight $\pm$50\% with renormalization preserves the rank order. This will likely change as agents improve and the truthfulness gate no longer dominates the variance budget; for now, it confirms that grounding, not quality, is the binding constraint.

\subsection{Error Analysis}
\label{sec:errors}

\textbf{GPT-Researcher} generates URLs that look like sandbox pages (e.g., \texttt{localhost:7770/product-name.html}) but with fabricated product names. Its parallel sub-query architecture appears to generate URL patterns from training data rather than from actual sandbox navigation; 97.5\% of its 1{,}870 cited URLs return HTTP errors.

\textbf{Langchain-ODR} (99.1\% fabrication) and \textbf{II-Researcher} (98.5\%) exhibit the same failure mode at greater intensity: their planner-style architectures emit reports that pattern-match on URL syntax rather than on results returned by the search shim.

\textbf{DeerFlow} cites only 406 URLs across 30 tasks (vs.\ 1{,}500--3{,}000 for the top tier) and fabricates 87\% of even those. Its multi-agent pipeline appears to skip the browse-and-verify step entirely under sandbox conditions.

\textbf{STORM} produces consistently empty outputs (20 bytes). Its knowledge-curation pipeline, designed for live Wikipedia and web APIs, fails to initialize when confined to the sandbox's search shim. This is a framework-integration issue, not a fundamental limitation.

\textbf{LDR} cites real URLs (89.6\% reachable) but only 67 of them across 30 tasks; the framework's lightweight design produces reports too short to satisfy the spec compliance dimension.

\textbf{CAMEL-AI}, \textbf{FlowSearcher}, and \textbf{SmolagentS} succeed because each separates search from synthesis: explicit tool-use agents issue search queries, receive real results, and pass verified URLs to the writing agent. CAMEL-AI achieves the highest reachability (91\%) and quote fidelity (78\%); FlowSearcher's hierarchical memory matches CAMEL-AI on spec compliance and presentation while citing half as many URLs; SmolagentS sits between them on every dimension.

% ======================================================================
\section{Limitations and Future Work}
\label{sec:limitations}

\paragraph{Ecological validity.} Sandbox evaluation trades realism for control. Agents optimized for live-web APIs may underperform when confined to a 200K-document corpus with a non-standard search shim. We view this as analogous to controlled experiments in medicine~\citep{deepresearchgym2025}: controlled conditions are necessary for causal claims about agent capabilities. \ours{} is intended to complement, not replace, live-web benchmarks.

\paragraph{Current data scope.} The Bradley-Terry leaderboard reported here is based on the 30-task $\times$ 9-agent common subset (270 head-to-head ground truths, 296 V3 score files including a 26-task extension for CAMEL-AI as a stability check). Per-dimension trends and the fluent-hallucinator finding are stable on the extended subset. The full 100-task $\times$ 9-agent matrix (${\sim}$900 evaluation runs) is in progress; the benchmark infrastructure (tasks, golden data, scoring) is complete and validated, and the remaining 70 tasks already have golden URL sets and quoted-span ground truth ready for scoring.

\paragraph{Single LLM judge.} Our checklist evaluation uses a single LLM (DeepSeek V4 flash). Best practice calls for multi-judge ensembles~\citep{draco2026,researchrubrics2025} with inter-judge agreement reporting~\citep{llmjudge2024}. Future work will add cross-family judges (e.g., GPT-5, Claude).

\paragraph{No human evaluation.} While our deterministic URL metrics reduce reliance on human judgment, the checklist dimension benefits from human validation of LLM-judge alignment. STORM~\citep{storm2024} used 10 Wikipedia editors; MindSearch~\citep{mindsearch2025} used 5 domain experts. A similar focused study is planned.

\paragraph{Source coverage.} Three sandbox sources (e-commerce, forum, encyclopedia) cover consumer and knowledge-intensive queries but not specialized domains such as legal databases, medical records, or code repositories. The modular architecture supports adding new sources.

% ======================================================================
\section{Broader Impact}
\label{sec:impact}

\ours{} is designed to improve the reliability of deep research agent evaluation. By providing deterministic ground truth and exposing citation fabrication, we aim to steer the field toward agents that are not only fluent but also truthful. The fluent hallucinator finding has implications beyond benchmarking: it suggests that deploying deep research agents in high-stakes domains (medicine, law, finance) without citation verification is risky, as users may trust well-formatted but fabricated references. Our benchmark and evaluation toolkit are released to support transparent, reproducible research.

% ======================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We introduced \ours{}, a reproducible benchmark for deep research agents built on a three-source interactive sandbox with deterministic citation ground truth. Our principal finding, the \emph{fluent hallucinator} phenomenon, reveals that standard text-quality evaluation misses a failure mode in which agents produce reports that outperform grounded competitors on every quality metric while fabricating $>$95\% of their citations. Only a truthfulness gate based on deterministic URL verification can detect this. We argue that (i)~sandbox-based evaluation is a necessary complement to live-web benchmarks~\citep{browsecomp_plus2025,deepresearchgym2025}, (ii)~citation truthfulness must be a first-class evaluation dimension~\citep{alce2023}, and (iii)~intent-type stratification enables deeper analysis of agent capabilities than flat task sets permit.

